				\begin{document}$$ \mathrm{hysteresis}\;\mathrm{index}=\frac{J_{\mathrm{RS}}\left(0.8{V}_{\mathrm{oc}}\right)-{J}_{\mathrm{FS}}\left(0.8{V}_{\mathrm{oc}}\right)}{J_{\mathrm{RS}}\left(0.8{V}_{\mathrm{oc}}\right)} $$\end{document}where JRS(0.8Voc) and JFS(0.8Voc) stand for the photocurrent density at 80% of Voc for the RS and FS, respectively. The calculated hysteresis index values are 0.164, 0.085, 0.019, and 0.066 for the I-V curves with the mole ratio of 1:3, 1.05:3, 1.1:3, and 1.15:3, respectively. With the increase of mole ratio, the hysteresis degree first decreases, and then increases. At the mole ratio of 1.1:3, the hysteresis index value is the smallest. The high PCE of 11.55% with less I-V hysteresis was obtained using the precursor solution with the mole ratio of 1.1:3.
